03957nam a22005415i 9780822394129DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223941297 a10.1515/97808223941292doi  a(DE-B1597)552885  a(OCoLC)727021239  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.F54 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4365561 aAuerbach, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDark Borders :bFilm Noir and American Citizenship /cJonathan Auerbach. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (279 p.) :b24 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tintroduction. The Un-Americanness of Film Noir -- tone. Gestapo in America -- ttwo. White-Collar Murder -- tthree. Cuba, Gangsters, Vets, and Other Outcasts of the Islands -- tfour. North from Mexico -- tfive. Bad Boy Patriots -- tpostscript. Darkness Visible -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDark Borders connects anxieties about citizenship and national belonging in midcentury America to the sense of alienation conveyed by American film noir. Jonathan Auerbach provides in-depth interpretations of more than a dozen of these dark crime thrillers, considering them in relation to U.S. national security measures enacted from the mid-1930s to the mid-1950s. The growth of a domestic intelligence-gathering apparatus before, during, and after the Second World War raised unsettling questions about who was American and who was not, and how to tell the difference. Auerbach shows how politics and aesthetics merge in these noirs, whose oft-noted uncanniness betrays the fear that "un-American" foes lurk within the homeland. This tone of dispossession was reflected in well-known films, including Double Indemnity, Out of the Past, and Pickup on South Street, and less familiar noirs such as Stranger on the Third Floor, The Chase, and Ride the Pink Horse. Whether tracing the consequences of the Gestapo in America, or the uncertain borderlines that separate the United States from Cuba and Mexico, these movies blur boundaries; inside and outside become confused as (presumed) foreigners take over domestic space. To feel like a stranger in your own home: this is the peculiar affective condition of citizenship intensified by wartime and Cold War security measures, as well as a primary mood driving many midcentury noir films.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aFilm noirzUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394129zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394129423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394129.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles